1
00:00:56,745 --> 00:01:00,748
It's obviously a
major malfunction.

2
00:01:15,762 --> 00:01:18,557
...their President is a
crook. Well, I'm not a crook.

3
00:01:22,476 --> 00:01:26,273
Robert Kennedy was
shot in that ballroom.

4
00:01:28,815 --> 00:01:31,234
Thank God Almighty,
we are free at last!

5
00:01:31,527 --> 00:01:34,363
A sniper has fired
at President Kennedy.

6
00:01:42,035 --> 00:01:46,206
Or have you ever been a
member of the Communist party?

7
00:01:50,544 --> 00:01:52,629
Hi-yo, Silver!

8
00:01:57,508 --> 00:01:59,259
...1941...

9
00:01:59,845 --> 00:02:03,181
...a date which
will live in infamy.

10
00:02:07,434 --> 00:02:09,511
We bring you the
final edition of

11
00:02:09,512 --> 00:02:11,772
our Maxwell House
Good News of 1939.

12
00:02:12,105 --> 00:02:13,846
Good evening,
Mr. and Mrs. North

13
00:02:13,847 --> 00:02:15,691
America, and all
the ships at sea.

14
00:02:20,821 --> 00:02:25,158
The only thing we have
to fear is fear itself.

15
00:03:32,470 --> 00:03:33,681
CQ...

16
00:03:34,054 --> 00:03:36,056
...this is W-9 GFO.

17
00:03:38,308 --> 00:03:41,687
CQ, this is W-9
GFO here. Come back?

18
00:03:45,691 --> 00:03:46,816
CQ...

19
00:03:47,024 --> 00:03:49,652
...this is W-9 GFO here.

20
00:03:50,529 --> 00:03:51,738
Come back?

21
00:03:55,658 --> 00:03:59,828
CQ, this is W-9 GFO.
Is anybody out there?

22
00:04:00,872 --> 00:04:01,997
Not getting anything.

23
00:04:02,288 --> 00:04:03,789
Small moves, Ellie.

24
00:04:05,417 --> 00:04:06,585
Small moves.

25
00:04:09,213 --> 00:04:12,964
CQ, this is W-9
GFO here. Come back?

26
00:04:13,925 --> 00:04:15,551
Copy, W-9 GFO.

27
00:04:15,759 --> 00:04:17,637
K-4 WLD here.

28
00:04:18,052 --> 00:04:19,471
What do I say?

29
00:04:19,679 --> 00:04:21,138
Just be yourself.

30
00:04:21,640 --> 00:04:24,308
Where are you,
K-4 WLD? Come back?

31
00:04:24,518 --> 00:04:25,810
Pensacola. Over.

32
00:04:26,059 --> 00:04:27,645
Pensacola, where's Pensacola?

33
00:04:27,978 --> 00:04:29,437
I'll give you a hint.

34
00:04:30,148 --> 00:04:31,274
Orange juice.

35
00:04:34,110 --> 00:04:37,737
Copy that, K-4 WLD. How's the
weather down there in Florida?

36
00:04:38,990 --> 00:04:40,949
Pensacola, Florida.

37
00:04:41,617 --> 00:04:43,452
I have to tell you, Sparks.

38
00:04:44,327 --> 00:04:46,622
1,116 miles.

39
00:04:48,165 --> 00:04:49,290
Pretty good.

40
00:04:49,583 --> 00:04:51,125
That's the farthest yet.

41
00:05:03,970 --> 00:05:05,846
Can we hear all
the way to New York?

42
00:05:06,097 --> 00:05:07,307
Sure.

43
00:05:08,682 --> 00:05:10,683
Can we hear all the
way to California?

44
00:05:10,934 --> 00:05:12,646
I don't see why not.

45
00:05:13,395 --> 00:05:15,396
Can we hear all
the way to Alaska?

46
00:05:15,773 --> 00:05:17,107
On a really clear day.

47
00:05:17,315 --> 00:05:19,317
Can we hear all
the way to China?

48
00:05:20,360 --> 00:05:22,820
On a really, really clear day.

49
00:05:24,656 --> 00:05:26,865
Could we talk to the moon?

50
00:05:27,450 --> 00:05:30,327
If it's a big enough
radio, I don't see why not.

51
00:05:30,993 --> 00:05:32,995
Could we talk to Jupiter?

52
00:05:33,204 --> 00:05:35,706
Or what's the one after that?

53
00:05:36,164 --> 00:05:37,459
Don't tell me.

54
00:05:39,877 --> 00:05:41,212
I'll give you a hint.

55
00:05:41,671 --> 00:05:42,839
Hula-Hoops.

56
00:05:43,047 --> 00:05:45,049
Saturn! Could we
talk to Saturn?

57
00:05:50,720 --> 00:05:53,225
Dad, could we talk to Mom?

58
00:05:58,855 --> 00:06:02,107
I don't think even the biggest
radio could reach that far.

59
00:06:07,112 --> 00:06:08,945
All right, no more stalling.

60
00:06:13,909 --> 00:06:15,368
Pensacola!

61
00:06:23,209 --> 00:06:24,461
That's a beauty.

62
00:06:25,920 --> 00:06:27,380
Now get some sleep.

63
00:06:35,721 --> 00:06:37,013
Hey, Dad?

64
00:06:38,098 --> 00:06:40,724
Do you think there's
people on other planets?

65
00:06:40,891 --> 00:06:42,602
I don't know, Sparks.

66
00:06:44,103 --> 00:06:45,731
But I guess I'd say...

67
00:06:46,271 --> 00:06:48,106
...if it is just us...

68
00:06:49,691 --> 00:06:51,944
...it seems like an
awful waste of space.

69
00:07:11,586 --> 00:07:13,963
CQ, this is W-9 GFO.

70
00:07:14,129 --> 00:07:16,760
Repeat. This is
W-9 GFO. Come back?

71
00:07:24,807 --> 00:07:26,810
I'm going to need
a bigger antenna.

72
00:07:53,833 --> 00:07:55,459
What do you think, Doc Arroway?

73
00:07:55,669 --> 00:07:57,168
Isn't she a beauty?

74
00:08:01,298 --> 00:08:02,425
It'll do.

75
00:08:02,632 --> 00:08:04,593
The village is five miles away.

76
00:08:04,801 --> 00:08:07,084
There's a general
store in the cantina.

77
00:08:07,084 --> 00:08:09,306
They can order
anything from San Juan.

78
00:08:09,513 --> 00:08:11,015
When can I get dish time?

79
00:08:11,182 --> 00:08:12,736
Dr. Clark said you couldn't

80
00:08:12,737 --> 00:08:14,809
wait. Your first
shift is tonight.

81
00:09:10,905 --> 00:09:12,070
Go back.

82
00:09:14,033 --> 00:09:16,743
Try back a little bit.
You had something there.

83
00:09:18,078 --> 00:09:19,079
There!

84
00:09:19,410 --> 00:09:20,244
- Right there?

85
00:09:20,244 --> 00:09:22,623
- You hear it? Right
there, that's it.

86
00:09:22,916 --> 00:09:26,585
All right, 1221.46. That's
well within the L-band.

87
00:09:26,918 --> 00:09:27,876
Check off-axis.

88
00:09:28,920 --> 00:09:30,045
On it.

89
00:09:31,756 --> 00:09:33,256
It's not in the neighborhood.

90
00:09:42,099 --> 00:09:44,101
Here it is. J-1741...

91
00:09:44,393 --> 00:09:46,060
...+ 2748.

92
00:09:46,268 --> 00:09:49,438
Catalogued November
4, 1982. Pulsar.

93
00:09:52,107 --> 00:09:55,235
Must've been the glitch in
the timing's what threw me.

94
00:09:55,486 --> 00:09:57,113
Must've been a starquake.

95
00:09:58,489 --> 00:10:00,143
I think it's great that you

96
00:10:00,144 --> 00:10:02,409
listen. Most don't
do that anymore.

97
00:10:02,617 --> 00:10:05,413
It's just an old habit.
It makes it feel more real.

98
00:10:05,620 --> 00:10:06,538
Ellie.

99
00:10:06,746 --> 00:10:07,914
Kent Clark.

100
00:10:10,791 --> 00:10:12,420
They said you'd been...

101
00:10:12,627 --> 00:10:15,087
...up at Owen's Valley
working under Drumlin.

102
00:10:15,255 --> 00:10:16,631
How'd you like him?

103
00:10:19,842 --> 00:10:21,817
That much? About
what I'd expect

104
00:10:21,818 --> 00:10:23,971
after what he had
to say about you.

105
00:10:24,304 --> 00:10:25,931
And what was that?

106
00:10:26,472 --> 00:10:27,973
That you are brilliant...

107
00:10:28,265 --> 00:10:29,475
...driven...

108
00:10:29,810 --> 00:10:31,311
...a major pain in the ass...

109
00:10:31,644 --> 00:10:33,017
...and obsessed with a field of

110
00:10:33,018 --> 00:10:34,522
study he considers
tantamount...

111
00:10:34,687 --> 00:10:36,106
...to professional suicide.

112
00:10:36,815 --> 00:10:37,816
Anything else?

113
00:10:38,025 --> 00:10:39,776
Those were the highlights.

114
00:10:40,318 --> 00:10:42,779
Davio, Dr. Vernon. Dr. Arroway.

115
00:10:44,321 --> 00:10:46,577
Believe you've already
met our tireless

116
00:10:46,578 --> 00:10:48,492
research assistant,
Mr. Fisher...

117
00:10:49,200 --> 00:10:51,494
...as well as his cologne.

118
00:10:52,162 --> 00:10:54,497
Brook's looking at
the black hole in M-87.

119
00:10:54,665 --> 00:10:58,502
Eli's studying Markarian
541, a major gamma ray source.

120
00:10:58,835 --> 00:11:00,899
Dr. Arroway will
be spending her

121
00:11:00,900 --> 00:11:03,465
precious telescope
time listening for...

122
00:11:04,214 --> 00:11:06,176
...listening for...

123
00:11:06,383 --> 00:11:07,886
Little green men.

124
00:11:15,933 --> 00:11:17,268
One down...

125
00:11:17,809 --> 00:11:19,520
...a couple billion to go.

126
00:11:36,328 --> 00:11:38,164
Arecibo, right?

127
00:11:39,330 --> 00:11:40,499
Does it show?

128
00:11:42,625 --> 00:11:43,793
Cracker Jack?

129
00:11:44,002 --> 00:11:44,795
No, thanks.

130
00:11:45,002 --> 00:11:46,296
Mind if I sit down?

131
00:11:48,214 --> 00:11:52,133
I hear the locals, they
call it "El Radar. "

132
00:11:52,343 --> 00:11:54,969
Convinced it has some
dark military purpose.

133
00:11:55,388 --> 00:11:56,805
I think we're harmless.

134
00:11:58,263 --> 00:11:59,432
Palmer Joss.

135
00:12:00,224 --> 00:12:02,727
- Ellie Arroway.
- Nice to meet you, Ellie.

136
00:12:03,894 --> 00:12:06,687
What are you studying up there?

137
00:12:08,564 --> 00:12:09,859
The usual.

138
00:12:10,067 --> 00:12:13,861
Nebulae, quasars,
pulsars, stuff like that.

139
00:12:14,278 --> 00:12:15,738
What are you writing?

140
00:12:16,071 --> 00:12:18,241
The usual. Nouns, adverbs...

141
00:12:18,450 --> 00:12:19,992
...adjective here and there.

142
00:12:21,744 --> 00:12:23,286
I work on a project, SETI.

143
00:12:24,079 --> 00:12:26,083
Search for Extraterrestrial
Intelligence?

144
00:12:28,250 --> 00:12:29,918
That is out there!

145
00:12:31,169 --> 00:12:33,463
Are you a student or something?

146
00:12:33,962 --> 00:12:36,091
I'm a writer. I'm
writing a book.

147
00:12:36,633 --> 00:12:38,713
I'm here doing
research about how

148
00:12:38,714 --> 00:12:41,220
technology affects
Third World cultures.

149
00:12:41,470 --> 00:12:44,099
I'm also looking for
this guy, David Drumlin.

150
00:12:44,432 --> 00:12:46,506
He's head of the
National Science

151
00:12:46,507 --> 00:12:48,519
Foundation. I
want an interview.

152
00:12:49,769 --> 00:12:51,522
I take it you know him?

153
00:12:52,940 --> 00:12:54,440
You could say that.

154
00:12:55,775 --> 00:12:57,277
SETI.

155
00:12:57,485 --> 00:12:59,155
That's fringe!

156
00:12:59,572 --> 00:13:01,869
I've crossed paths
with him. Something

157
00:13:01,870 --> 00:13:03,991
like that must
really chap his ass.

158
00:13:06,951 --> 00:13:07,995
Compass.

159
00:13:09,998 --> 00:13:11,290
That's for you.

160
00:13:16,170 --> 00:13:17,629
You better keep this.

161
00:13:18,837 --> 00:13:20,505
Might save your life someday.

162
00:13:25,303 --> 00:13:26,887
Have dinner with me tonight?

163
00:13:29,848 --> 00:13:33,142
I don't make a good research
subject. I'm not quotable.

164
00:13:33,477 --> 00:13:35,771
No quotes. Scout's honor.

165
00:13:36,187 --> 00:13:37,480
Good meal, good company.

166
00:13:38,354 --> 00:13:39,648
I've got to go.

167
00:13:48,822 --> 00:13:50,617
Drumlin's coming in Tuesday.

168
00:13:59,541 --> 00:14:02,879
Now I remember why
I took that desk job.

169
00:14:04,421 --> 00:14:06,424
Dr. Drumlin, how are you?

170
00:14:08,008 --> 00:14:09,551
Glad you could make it.

171
00:14:10,719 --> 00:14:13,680
If I'd known it took 3 planes,
I might've reconsidered.

172
00:14:13,888 --> 00:14:15,223
How is that new office?

173
00:14:15,432 --> 00:14:17,677
Still settling in.
They already want

174
00:14:17,678 --> 00:14:20,102
to give half my
budget to the Pentagon.

175
00:14:20,853 --> 00:14:23,230
Still waiting for E.T. to call?

176
00:14:25,232 --> 00:14:26,858
Good to see you too!

177
00:14:27,400 --> 00:14:28,401
Asshole!

178
00:14:28,650 --> 00:14:30,861
Looks like it's going
to be a long night.

179
00:14:31,072 --> 00:14:33,343
Science must be
accountable to the

180
00:14:33,344 --> 00:14:35,741
people paying for
it, the taxpayers.

181
00:14:35,908 --> 00:14:39,202
We must stop wasting money on
pie-in-the-sky abstractions...

182
00:14:39,371 --> 00:14:42,205
...and spend it on
practical, measurable ways...

183
00:14:42,373 --> 00:14:45,083
...to improve the lives of
the people who are paying.

184
00:14:45,250 --> 00:14:48,461
Not unlike my L-band,
globular clusters work.

185
00:14:48,712 --> 00:14:51,673
You want to do away with
all pure research now?

186
00:14:51,880 --> 00:14:55,260
What's wrong with science being
practical? Even profitable?

187
00:14:55,467 --> 00:14:57,594
Nothing, as long
as your motive...

188
00:14:57,886 --> 00:14:59,796
...is the search
for truth. Which

189
00:14:59,797 --> 00:15:01,764
is what the pursuit
of science is.

190
00:15:04,393 --> 00:15:06,770
That's an interesting
position from a man...

191
00:15:06,978 --> 00:15:09,604
...on a crusade against
the evils of technology...

192
00:15:09,897 --> 00:15:11,024
...Father Joss.

193
00:15:11,690 --> 00:15:15,028
I'm not against technology,
Doctor. I'm against...

194
00:15:15,236 --> 00:15:18,487
...the men who deify it at
the expense of human truth.

195
00:15:22,576 --> 00:15:25,953
Kent, I need to have a word
with you. Over here, please.

196
00:15:31,626 --> 00:15:34,755
You think that hurt my
chances with that interview?

197
00:15:35,378 --> 00:15:36,797
You're a priest?

198
00:15:38,716 --> 00:15:39,884
Not really.

199
00:15:40,633 --> 00:15:43,387
I got my Masters in Divinity...

200
00:15:43,887 --> 00:15:47,307
...then left the seminary to
do secular humanitarian work...

201
00:15:47,557 --> 00:15:49,976
...coordinating
Third World churches.

202
00:15:50,727 --> 00:15:52,770
I couldn't live with
the celibacy thing.

203
00:15:57,399 --> 00:15:59,442
You could call me
a man of the cloth...

204
00:16:00,735 --> 00:16:02,279
...without the cloth.

205
00:16:05,656 --> 00:16:07,241
You want to get out of here?

206
00:16:09,243 --> 00:16:11,163
You see that large W-shaped

207
00:16:11,164 --> 00:16:14,081
constellation there?
That's Cassiopeia.

208
00:16:14,498 --> 00:16:18,919
And Cassiopeia A gives off
a whole lot of radio signals.

209
00:16:19,251 --> 00:16:20,920
I listen to them a lot.

210
00:16:21,171 --> 00:16:23,465
It's a remnant of a supernova.

211
00:16:24,465 --> 00:16:27,092
When did you know you
wanted to be an astronomer?

212
00:16:29,470 --> 00:16:31,722
When I was about
eight years old...

213
00:16:31,931 --> 00:16:34,358
...watching the
sunset, I asked Dad,

214
00:16:34,359 --> 00:16:36,851
"What's that bright
star over there?"

215
00:16:40,313 --> 00:16:43,440
He said that it wasn't
a star. It was...

216
00:16:45,361 --> 00:16:47,779
...a whole planet
called Venus...

217
00:16:51,407 --> 00:16:54,618
...which should
be over there soon.

218
00:16:55,619 --> 00:16:57,995
He said, "You know why
they called it Venus?

219
00:16:58,455 --> 00:17:01,667
Because they thought it was
so beautiful and glowing.

220
00:17:01,958 --> 00:17:03,501
But they didn't know...

221
00:17:04,210 --> 00:17:06,838
...that it's filled with...

222
00:17:08,088 --> 00:17:11,466
...deadly gases and
sulfuric acid rain. "

223
00:17:12,802 --> 00:17:16,304
Wow, I thought, "This
is it! I'm hooked!"

224
00:17:18,557 --> 00:17:22,185
There are four hundred
billion stars out there...

225
00:17:22,477 --> 00:17:24,311
...just in our galaxy alone.

226
00:17:25,312 --> 00:17:28,982
If only one out of a million
of those had planets...

227
00:17:29,400 --> 00:17:32,527
...if just one out of a
million of those had life...

228
00:17:32,694 --> 00:17:34,871
...and if just one
out of a million

229
00:17:34,872 --> 00:17:36,865
of those had
intelligent life...

230
00:17:37,657 --> 00:17:40,167
...there would be
literally millions

231
00:17:40,168 --> 00:17:42,202
of civilizations out there...

232
00:17:44,121 --> 00:17:45,664
If there wasn't...

233
00:17:46,582 --> 00:17:48,751
...it'd be an awful
waste of space.

234
00:17:54,673 --> 00:17:55,882
Amen.

235
00:18:04,806 --> 00:18:08,769
So I was lying there,
just looking at the sky.

236
00:18:12,690 --> 00:18:15,692
And then I felt
something. I don't know.

237
00:18:17,027 --> 00:18:19,696
All I know is that
I wasn't alone.

238
00:18:20,072 --> 00:18:24,282
For the first time in my life
I wasn't scared of nothing...

239
00:18:25,243 --> 00:18:26,827
...not even dying.

240
00:18:32,458 --> 00:18:34,250
It was God.

241
00:18:37,003 --> 00:18:38,962
And there's no chance that...

242
00:18:39,464 --> 00:18:41,583
...you had this
experience because

243
00:18:41,584 --> 00:18:43,759
some part of you
needed to have it?

244
00:18:44,968 --> 00:18:48,429
I'm a reasonably
intelligent guy, but this...

245
00:18:51,308 --> 00:18:54,976
My intellect couldn't
even touch this.

246
00:18:55,521 --> 00:18:56,479
No.

247
00:18:58,982 --> 00:19:01,609
I've been to Sunday
school a few times.

248
00:19:03,820 --> 00:19:04,695
And?

249
00:19:04,903 --> 00:19:09,448
I kept asking all these really
annoying questions like...

250
00:19:10,367 --> 00:19:12,785
..."Where did Mrs.
Cain come from?"

251
00:19:14,744 --> 00:19:17,081
And pretty soon
they asked my dad...

252
00:19:17,249 --> 00:19:20,041
...if he wouldn't mind
keeping me home from now on.

253
00:19:20,251 --> 00:19:21,584
Your dad...

254
00:19:23,254 --> 00:19:24,838
Is it this guy?

255
00:19:25,047 --> 00:19:26,213
Yeah.

256
00:19:28,342 --> 00:19:30,344
You're close to
him, aren't you?

257
00:19:31,721 --> 00:19:34,806
I was. He died when
I was nine years old.

258
00:19:37,017 --> 00:19:38,976
I never got to know my mother.

259
00:19:40,645 --> 00:19:41,938
I'm sorry.

260
00:19:46,483 --> 00:19:48,402
That's got to be tough.

261
00:19:52,865 --> 00:19:54,490
Being alone.

262
00:20:03,373 --> 00:20:04,623
What do you say...

263
00:20:04,874 --> 00:20:08,337
...we pack a picnic tomorrow
and hike up to Mount Arecibo?

264
00:20:09,211 --> 00:20:12,214
I don't think I can.
I've got to work.

265
00:20:14,008 --> 00:20:17,428
How about dinner tomorrow
night? I know a great dive.

266
00:20:17,845 --> 00:20:19,387
No, I don't think so.

267
00:20:24,060 --> 00:20:26,226
Ellie, did I miss something?

268
00:20:28,395 --> 00:20:29,522
No.

269
00:20:29,730 --> 00:20:31,566
Shit, I'm late!

270
00:20:32,567 --> 00:20:35,444
I told Kent that I'd
be there at 10:30.

271
00:20:38,112 --> 00:20:39,907
I'm not trying to push you.

272
00:20:40,114 --> 00:20:42,368
I've wanted to look at
this sector for weeks.

273
00:20:42,575 --> 00:20:44,242
Just hang out...

274
00:20:44,577 --> 00:20:47,538
...and sleep in. There's
food in the fridge.

275
00:20:49,250 --> 00:20:50,334
How can I reach you?

276
00:20:51,958 --> 00:20:54,212
Just leave your
number. I'll call you.

277
00:21:16,022 --> 00:21:16,981
Dad!

278
00:21:19,026 --> 00:21:21,570
It's starting, you're
going to miss it!

279
00:21:25,156 --> 00:21:27,366
Dad, there's another
one! Hurry up!

280
00:21:27,533 --> 00:21:29,911
In a minute, Sparks!
I'm almost done.

281
00:21:30,161 --> 00:21:32,622
There's another one.
Come on, hurry up, Dad!

282
00:22:28,298 --> 00:22:29,467
I'll get the medicine.

283
00:23:49,204 --> 00:23:51,916
I know it's hard to
understand this now...

284
00:23:52,875 --> 00:23:55,218
...but we aren't
always meant to know

285
00:23:55,219 --> 00:23:57,379
why things happen
the way they do.

286
00:23:57,920 --> 00:24:00,215
Sometimes, we just
have to accept it...

287
00:24:00,423 --> 00:24:02,259
...as God's will.

288
00:24:04,218 --> 00:24:07,389
I should have kept medicine
in the downstairs bathroom.

289
00:24:08,055 --> 00:24:10,266
Then I could've
gotten to it sooner.

290
00:24:36,122 --> 00:24:37,456
CQ...

291
00:24:38,624 --> 00:24:41,627
...this is W-9
GFO. Do you copy?

292
00:24:45,255 --> 00:24:47,548
Dad, this is Ellie. Come back.

293
00:24:50,968 --> 00:24:52,887
This is Eleanor Arroway...

294
00:24:53,137 --> 00:24:56,140
...transmitting
on 14.2 megahertz.

295
00:25:02,855 --> 00:25:04,314
Are you there?

296
00:25:06,525 --> 00:25:07,901
Come back.

297
00:25:14,658 --> 00:25:16,076
Are you there?

298
00:25:17,160 --> 00:25:19,036
Dad, this is Ellie.

299
00:25:51,607 --> 00:25:54,526
Hi, Kent. What are
you doing up so early?

300
00:25:55,652 --> 00:25:56,988
I was thinking...

301
00:25:57,862 --> 00:25:59,864
...we'd make a
pretty good team.

302
00:26:00,532 --> 00:26:04,120
We could put together
an ad hoc SETI program.

303
00:26:04,328 --> 00:26:06,621
You know the Very Large
Array in New Mexico?

304
00:26:06,870 --> 00:26:09,164
It's a dynamite place
to do SETI work...

305
00:26:09,373 --> 00:26:11,165
What are you talking about?

306
00:26:13,585 --> 00:26:15,337
Drumlin pulled the plug.

307
00:26:16,089 --> 00:26:17,090
We're homeless.

308
00:26:31,394 --> 00:26:33,021
It's true, you pulled the plug?

309
00:26:33,229 --> 00:26:35,772
You can't see it now,
but I'm doing you a favor.

310
00:26:35,981 --> 00:26:38,012
You're too promising
a scientist to

311
00:26:38,013 --> 00:26:39,986
waste your gifts
on this nonsense.

312
00:26:40,235 --> 00:26:42,236
I don't consider
what could be...

313
00:26:42,446 --> 00:26:45,282
...the most important
human discovery nonsense!

314
00:26:45,573 --> 00:26:46,908
400 billion stars...

315
00:26:47,159 --> 00:26:50,078
And two probabilities. One,
there's intelligent life...

316
00:26:50,286 --> 00:26:52,704
...but too far away to
contact in your lifetime.

317
00:26:53,413 --> 00:26:55,333
- And two!
- You're making a decision...

318
00:26:55,791 --> 00:26:57,914
There's nothing
but gases and carbon

319
00:26:57,915 --> 00:27:00,211
compounds and you're
wasting your time!

320
00:27:00,420 --> 00:27:03,382
In the meantime, you
won't be taken seriously.

321
00:27:03,590 --> 00:27:05,257
Your career will be over!

322
00:27:05,466 --> 00:27:06,676
So what?

323
00:27:06,968 --> 00:27:08,385
It's my life!

324
00:27:46,129 --> 00:27:48,632
Hey, Kent. You were right.

325
00:27:49,006 --> 00:27:50,914
Screw Drumlin.
We'll raise the money

326
00:27:50,915 --> 00:27:52,719
ourselves. We'll
go to New Mexico.

327
00:27:52,969 --> 00:27:55,262
Chicago's set. Let
me know how it goes.

328
00:27:55,513 --> 00:27:58,430
I've got more corporate stops
on the East Coast for you.

329
00:27:58,640 --> 00:28:01,769
Did that investor from
Houston ever get back to us?

330
00:28:01,936 --> 00:28:03,937
I'll hit him up
on my way to L.A.

331
00:28:04,145 --> 00:28:06,313
Beg for some of
that Hollywood money!

332
00:28:06,523 --> 00:28:09,609
They've been making money
off aliens for years.

333
00:28:10,235 --> 00:28:12,861
- Begging is good for the soul.
- We'll see.

334
00:28:13,237 --> 00:28:14,863
Just do me a favor.

335
00:28:15,238 --> 00:28:17,699
Try not to be too...
confrontational.

336
00:28:18,200 --> 00:28:20,493
Confrontational?
Me? What do you mean?

337
00:28:20,702 --> 00:28:22,328
I'll see if I left anything.

338
00:28:55,650 --> 00:28:57,540
It's a unique time
in our history,

339
00:28:57,541 --> 00:28:59,488
in the history of
any civilization.

340
00:28:59,655 --> 00:29:02,448
It's the moment of the
acquisition of technology.

341
00:29:02,616 --> 00:29:05,492
That's the moment where
contact becomes possible.

342
00:29:06,284 --> 00:29:08,537
The Very Large Array
in New Mexico...

343
00:29:08,788 --> 00:29:11,040
...is the key to our
chances for success.

344
00:29:11,249 --> 00:29:13,334
With its 27 linked
radio telescopes...

345
00:29:13,583 --> 00:29:15,502
...we can search
more accurately

346
00:29:15,503 --> 00:29:17,129
than at any other facility.

347
00:29:17,295 --> 00:29:19,550
We've gotten
approval to buy the

348
00:29:19,551 --> 00:29:22,007
telescope time
from the government.

349
00:29:22,883 --> 00:29:25,052
Now all we really
need is the money.

350
00:29:25,803 --> 00:29:27,805
A nice presentation, Doctor.

351
00:29:28,513 --> 00:29:31,515
But while our foundation arm
has a mandate to support...

352
00:29:31,725 --> 00:29:34,811
...experimental
programs, your proposal...

353
00:29:35,061 --> 00:29:39,065
...seems less like science,
and more like science fiction.

354
00:29:41,568 --> 00:29:42,985
Science fiction.

355
00:29:46,446 --> 00:29:47,822
You're right.

356
00:29:48,615 --> 00:29:49,992
It's crazy.

357
00:29:51,076 --> 00:29:53,661
In fact, it's even
worse than that: nuts!

358
00:29:55,747 --> 00:29:57,207
Want to hear something nutty?

359
00:29:57,373 --> 00:29:59,917
Two guys wanted to build
a thing called an airplane.

360
00:30:00,125 --> 00:30:03,169
People go in it and fly like
birds. Ridiculous, right?

361
00:30:03,420 --> 00:30:05,171
What about breaking
the sound barrier...

362
00:30:05,421 --> 00:30:07,035
...or rockets to the moon, or

363
00:30:07,036 --> 00:30:09,092
atomic energy or
a mission to Mars?

364
00:30:09,343 --> 00:30:10,969
Science fiction, right?

365
00:30:12,762 --> 00:30:14,889
All I'm asking
is for you to just

366
00:30:14,890 --> 00:30:16,890
have the tiniest bit of vision.

367
00:30:17,264 --> 00:30:20,602
To step back and look
at the big picture.

368
00:30:20,979 --> 00:30:23,602
Take a chance on
something which could

369
00:30:23,603 --> 00:30:26,025
end up the most
impactful moment...

370
00:30:26,276 --> 00:30:28,569
...for humanity,
for the history...

371
00:30:29,194 --> 00:30:30,486
...of history.

372
00:30:34,282 --> 00:30:35,284
I'm sorry.

373
00:30:36,367 --> 00:30:37,994
I just spent 13 months...

374
00:30:38,618 --> 00:30:41,455
...coming into rooms and
talking to people like you.

375
00:30:42,330 --> 00:30:43,708
You're my last chance.

376
00:30:45,167 --> 00:30:46,751
Sorry I wasted your time.

377
00:30:46,960 --> 00:30:47,543
Doctor.

378
00:30:48,421 --> 00:30:49,504
Yes, sir.

379
00:31:01,849 --> 00:31:03,099
You have your money.

380
00:31:06,144 --> 00:31:07,313
Thank you.

381
00:31:09,397 --> 00:31:10,399
Thank you.

382
00:31:58,400 --> 00:32:01,402
Perfect cast! Come on, fishy!

383
00:32:01,652 --> 00:32:03,154
Frank, look at the size...

384
00:32:03,365 --> 00:32:05,366
...of that
son-of-a-bitch!

385
00:32:17,793 --> 00:32:19,752
Welcome back, Dr. C.

386
00:32:20,003 --> 00:32:21,505
How'd it go?

387
00:32:22,172 --> 00:32:23,757
How was the trip?

388
00:32:24,006 --> 00:32:25,424
I've had better.

389
00:32:26,050 --> 00:32:29,096
Drumlin! Is this a
personal vendetta now?

390
00:32:29,345 --> 00:32:33,181
There's been enormous pressure
from other scientists as well.

391
00:32:33,390 --> 00:32:36,517
It doesn't matter. Hadden's
funding us for 2 more years.

392
00:32:36,728 --> 00:32:38,768
The government
doesn't want their

393
00:32:38,769 --> 00:32:41,231
telescopes used by
the high priestess...

394
00:32:41,439 --> 00:32:43,441
...of the desert anymore.

395
00:32:44,774 --> 00:32:45,735
What?

396
00:32:45,902 --> 00:32:49,238
Staring at TV static for hours,
listening to washing machines.

397
00:32:49,487 --> 00:32:51,489
These stories get out!

398
00:32:51,698 --> 00:32:53,367
I was seeking
patterns in the chaos!

399
00:32:53,534 --> 00:32:55,620
It doesn't matter,
we're a joke to them.

400
00:32:55,828 --> 00:32:57,204
They want us out!

401
00:32:58,997 --> 00:33:01,875
We've got 3 months till
the paperwork goes through.

402
00:33:05,712 --> 00:33:07,880
I'll start looking
for other funding.

403
00:33:08,422 --> 00:33:12,176
Could you face reality?
Just this once? We lost.

404
00:33:12,926 --> 00:33:14,220
It's over.

405
00:33:20,892 --> 00:33:22,059
Fine.

406
00:33:22,727 --> 00:33:24,311
I'm not stopping.

407
00:33:24,895 --> 00:33:27,983
If I have to, I'll go it
alone. I've done it before.

408
00:34:17,693 --> 00:34:21,406
My guest tonight is author
and theologian Palmer Joss.

409
00:34:21,738 --> 00:34:24,157
He's become a
spiritual counselor, and

410
00:34:24,158 --> 00:34:26,452
a recent fixture
at the White House.

411
00:34:26,744 --> 00:34:29,706
"God's Diplomat," according
to The New York Times.

412
00:34:29,913 --> 00:34:31,932
His latest book,
"Losing Faith,"

413
00:34:31,933 --> 00:34:33,585
is currently number one...

414
00:34:33,793 --> 00:34:36,087
...on that publication's
bestseller list.

415
00:34:36,294 --> 00:34:39,255
Thanks for being here.
You've had quite a ride...

416
00:34:39,463 --> 00:34:40,965
...the last few years.

417
00:34:41,132 --> 00:34:42,842
Yeah, I sure have, Larry.

418
00:34:43,634 --> 00:34:45,844
Fish, I was thinking.

419
00:34:46,262 --> 00:34:50,600
Who would make the best
astronomers? Think about it.

420
00:34:50,932 --> 00:34:55,729
Who has the perfect synthesis
of career and lifestyle?

421
00:34:56,938 --> 00:34:57,898
I give.

422
00:34:58,105 --> 00:34:59,649
Vampires!

423
00:34:59,983 --> 00:35:02,526
Are you anti-technology
and anti-science?

424
00:35:02,777 --> 00:35:04,444
No, not at all.

425
00:35:04,779 --> 00:35:07,572
The question that
I'm asking is this:

426
00:35:08,323 --> 00:35:09,783
Are we happier...

427
00:35:10,450 --> 00:35:12,229
...as a human
race? Is the world

428
00:35:12,230 --> 00:35:13,953
fundamentally a better place...

429
00:35:14,161 --> 00:35:16,164
...because of science
and technology?

430
00:35:16,831 --> 00:35:19,292
We shop at home,
we surf the Web...

431
00:35:19,458 --> 00:35:22,127
...but at the same
time we feel emptier...

432
00:35:22,460 --> 00:35:24,684
...and more cut
off from each other

433
00:35:24,685 --> 00:35:27,215
than at any other
time in human history.

434
00:35:27,465 --> 00:35:30,009
We're becoming a
synthesized society...

435
00:35:30,301 --> 00:35:32,470
...in a hurry to get to the...

436
00:35:47,191 --> 00:35:48,862
We're looking for the meaning.

437
00:35:49,193 --> 00:35:50,486
What is the meaning?

438
00:35:50,654 --> 00:35:53,406
We have mindless jobs,
take frantic vacations.

439
00:35:53,823 --> 00:35:56,783
Deficit finance trips to
the mall to buy things...

440
00:35:57,036 --> 00:36:00,580
...that we think will fill
these holes in our lives.

441
00:36:01,039 --> 00:36:03,457
Any wonder we've lost
our sense of direction?

442
00:36:44,327 --> 00:36:45,995
Holy shit!

443
00:37:04,304 --> 00:37:05,263
Right ascension...

444
00:37:05,472 --> 00:37:09,351
...18 hours, 36
minutes, 56.2 seconds!

445
00:37:10,477 --> 00:37:12,143
Declination...

446
00:37:12,437 --> 00:37:15,398
...+ 36 degrees, 46 minutes...

447
00:37:15,774 --> 00:37:17,983
...56.2 seconds!

448
00:37:20,485 --> 00:37:21,946
Confirm!

449
00:37:22,153 --> 00:37:25,240
Right ascension, 18
hours, 36 minutes...

450
00:37:25,406 --> 00:37:27,575
...56.2 seconds!

451
00:37:28,243 --> 00:37:31,079
Is anybody awake in there?
I'm moving the array!

452
00:37:31,288 --> 00:37:33,248
- Confirm!

453
00:37:33,456 --> 00:37:34,957
Boss has a bogey!

454
00:37:35,165 --> 00:37:37,377
Right ascension, 18 hours...

455
00:37:41,840 --> 00:37:43,046
We're on it!

456
00:37:43,256 --> 00:37:44,215
36 hours...

457
00:37:44,674 --> 00:37:46,634
...47 minutes and 1 second!

458
00:37:47,094 --> 00:37:48,428
Strong possible...

459
00:37:48,636 --> 00:37:51,139
...pulse chain
on sub-array four!

460
00:37:51,345 --> 00:37:53,848
I'm moving the rest.
Confirm coordinates!

461
00:37:54,809 --> 00:37:56,685
Check the status of the array.

462
00:37:56,977 --> 00:37:58,352
She's doing all the dishes.

463
00:37:58,769 --> 00:37:59,646
Systems nominal.

464
00:38:05,526 --> 00:38:06,651
Hello.

465
00:38:07,904 --> 00:38:08,945
Full systems check!

466
00:38:09,821 --> 00:38:12,491
Coordinates confirmed.
Willie's checking the system.

467
00:38:12,824 --> 00:38:15,659
Stay on top of the
systems diagnostics!

468
00:38:15,952 --> 00:38:17,662
Check reference point offsets.

469
00:38:17,870 --> 00:38:21,874
And I want you off-axis on
27 the second we get there!

470
00:38:22,042 --> 00:38:24,543
And tell Willie to
break out the big boy!

471
00:38:26,127 --> 00:38:27,170
Copy that.

472
00:38:28,673 --> 00:38:29,966
Yeah! Go, Ellie!

473
00:38:30,174 --> 00:38:33,343
I hear it on the headphones.
We got to be sure about this.

474
00:38:33,678 --> 00:38:35,847
Give me another array status.

475
00:38:37,681 --> 00:38:41,185
Her four are online,
the rest are tracking in.

476
00:38:43,686 --> 00:38:46,023
But there's a bad drive on 16.

477
00:38:46,231 --> 00:38:48,650
The four are online,
the rest are tracking in.

478
00:38:48,941 --> 00:38:51,736
There's a bad drive
on 16. Copy that?

479
00:38:53,195 --> 00:38:55,196
What shall I do about
the source queue?

480
00:38:55,405 --> 00:38:57,365
Forget it and hold the queue.

481
00:38:57,699 --> 00:38:59,840
Get ready to set
the target frequency

482
00:38:59,841 --> 00:39:01,870
to manual the
second we're aligned.

483
00:39:02,078 --> 00:39:03,919
Do you copy? I want you to go

484
00:39:03,920 --> 00:39:06,457
off-axis on 27 the
second we're there!

485
00:39:06,706 --> 00:39:09,336
And leave the LO
frequency where it is!

486
00:39:09,709 --> 00:39:12,836
Don't let it get away! If
you lose it, scan the band!

487
00:39:13,047 --> 00:39:15,673
Run every frequency
you can think of.

488
00:39:21,054 --> 00:39:22,346
How you doing?

489
00:39:26,935 --> 00:39:28,061
Talk to me, guys.

490
00:39:28,269 --> 00:39:31,939
Partially polarized moving
pulses, amplitude modulated.

491
00:39:32,146 --> 00:39:35,817
We're locked. Systems are
fine. What's the frequency?

492
00:39:36,067 --> 00:39:37,025
4.46...

493
00:39:37,278 --> 00:39:38,778
...23 gigahertz.

494
00:39:40,572 --> 00:39:42,196
Hydrogen times pi.

495
00:39:42,575 --> 00:39:43,700
Told you!

496
00:39:43,992 --> 00:39:45,659
Strong sucker too!

497
00:39:46,742 --> 00:39:48,286
I got it! I'm patched in!

498
00:39:48,996 --> 00:39:50,037
Let me hear.

499
00:39:55,711 --> 00:39:57,129
Listen to that.

500
00:39:59,424 --> 00:40:01,382
Make me a liar, Fish.

501
00:40:01,841 --> 00:40:04,552
It could be AWACS out
of Kirkland jamming us.

502
00:40:04,802 --> 00:40:05,969
But I doubt it.

503
00:40:06,219 --> 00:40:08,389
See if F.U.D.D.'s
reading it too.

504
00:40:10,473 --> 00:40:12,559
Patch it back and
give me the off-axis.

505
00:40:13,185 --> 00:40:14,852
- We recording?
- Never stopped.

506
00:40:16,939 --> 00:40:18,232
Thank you, Elmer!

507
00:40:18,440 --> 00:40:20,233
AWACS status is negative.

508
00:40:20,442 --> 00:40:21,443
White Sands?

509
00:40:21,650 --> 00:40:23,276
On this frequency? No.

510
00:40:23,735 --> 00:40:25,071
I'll punch up the darks.

511
00:40:28,281 --> 00:40:29,449
How's spying tonight?

512
00:40:30,534 --> 00:40:31,868
Come on!

513
00:40:34,246 --> 00:40:36,623
NORAD's not tracking any
snoops in this vector.

514
00:40:37,081 --> 00:40:38,457
Shuttle's in sleep mode.

515
00:40:38,791 --> 00:40:40,961
Okay, point source confirmed.

516
00:40:41,253 --> 00:40:42,837
Whatever it is, it ain't local.

517
00:40:43,086 --> 00:40:43,878
Position?

518
00:40:44,088 --> 00:40:46,548
I checked interferometry.
Somewhere in Lyra.

519
00:40:46,756 --> 00:40:48,424
- Vega?
- Can't be!

520
00:40:48,634 --> 00:40:50,636
It's only 26 light years away.

521
00:40:50,927 --> 00:40:52,846
- Peak intensity?
- Coming up!

522
00:40:54,096 --> 00:40:54,805
